# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: erp-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business processes occur at all organizational levels and may or may not be visible to the customers.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] A business process may often be visualized (modeled) as a flowchart of a sequence of activities with interleaving decision points or as a process matrix of a sequence of activities with relevance rules based on data in the process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The benefits of using business processes include improved customer satisfaction and improved agility for reacting to rapid market change.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Process-oriented organizations break down the barriers of structural departments and try to avoid functional silos.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] A business process begins with a mission objective (an external event) and ends with achievement of the business objective of providing a result that provides customer value.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Additionally, a process may be divided into subprocesses (process decomposition), the particular inner functions of the process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business processes may also have a process owner, a responsible party for ensuring the process runs smoothly from start to finish.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Operational processes, which are business processes, are of a productive or "missional" nature.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] These processes generate a product or service to be delivered to customers.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] These are considered to be unique or specific to each organisation.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Support processes, which are auxiliary in nature, support for operational and strategic processes.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] These are responsible for providing resources and are presented in most organizations.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] A business made up of many process may be decomposed into various subprocesses, each of which have their own peculiar aspects but also contribute to achieving the objectives of the business.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The business review analyzes processes, that usually include the mapping or modeling of processes and sub-processes down to a group of activities at different levels.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Processes can be modeled using a large number of methods and techniques.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] For instance, the Business Process Modeling Notation is a business process modeling technique that can be used for drawing business processes in a visualized workflow.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] While decomposing processes into process classifications, categories can be helpful, but care must be taken in doing so as there may be crossover.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] At last, all processes are part of a largely unified customer-focused result, one of "customer value creation." This goal is expedited with business process management, which aims to analyze, improve, and enact business processes.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] An important early (1776) description of processes was that of economist Adam Smith in his famous example of a pin factory.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Smith also first recognized how output could be increased through the use of labor division.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Previously, in a society where production was dominated by handcrafted goods, one man would perform all the activities required during the production process, while Smith described how the work was divided into a set of simple tasks which would be performed by specialized workers.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The result of labor division in Smith's example resulted in productivity increasing by 24,000 percent (sic), i.e. that the same number of workers made 240 times as many pins as they had been producing before the introduction of labor division.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Smith did not advocate labor division at any price or *per se*.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The appropriate level of task division was defined through experimental design of the production process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] In contrast to Smith's view which was limited to the same functional domain and comprised activities that are in direct sequence in the manufacturing process, today's process concept includes cross-functionality as an important characteristic.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Following his ideas, the division of labor was adopted widely, while the integration of tasks into a functional, or cross-functional, process was not considered as an alternative option until much later.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] American engineer Frederick Winslow Taylor greatly influenced and improved the quality of industrial processes in the early twentieth century.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] His Principles of Scientific Management focused on standardization of processes, systematic training and clearly defining the roles of management and employees.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] His methods were widely adopted in the United States, Russia and parts of Europe and led to further developments such as "time and motion study" and visual task optimization techniques, such as Gantt charts.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] In the latter part of the twentieth century, management guru Peter Drucker focused much of his work on the simplification and decentralization of processes, which led to the concept of outsourcing.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] He also coined the concept of the "knowledge worker," as differentiated from manual workers – and how knowledge management would become part of an entity's processes.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] This definition contains certain characteristics that a process must possess.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] These characteristics are achieved by focusing on the business logic of the process (how work is done) instead of taking a product perspective (what is done).
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Hammer & Champy's (1993) definition can be considered as a subset of Davenport's.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] As we can note, Hammer & Champy have a more transformation-oriented perception and put less emphasis on the structural component – process boundaries and the order of activities in time and space.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The above definition distinguishes two types of processes, primary and support processes, depending on whether a process is directly involved in the creation of customer value or concerned with the organization's internal activities.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] In this sense, Rummler and Brache's definition follows Porter's value chain model, which also builds on a division of primary and secondary activities.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] According to Rummler and Brache, a typical characteristic of a successful process-based organization is the absence of secondary activities in the primary value flow that is created in the customer oriented primary processes.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The characteristic of processes as spanning the white space on the organization chart indicates that processes are embedded in some form of organizational structure.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Also, a process can be cross-functional, i.e. it ranges over several business functions.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] This definition also emphasizes the constitution of links between activities and the transformation that takes place within the process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Johansson et al. also include the upstream part of the value chain as a possible recipient of the process output.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] *Order*: It must consist of activities that are ordered according to their position in time and space (a sequence).
[src:erp-systems/business-process] *Customer*: There must be a recipient of the process' outcome, a customer.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] *Value-adding*: The transformation taking place within the process must add value to the recipient, either upstream or downstream.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] *Embeddedness*: A process cannot exist in itself, it must be embedded in an organizational structure.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] *Cross-functionality*: A process regularly can, but not necessarily must, span several functions.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Frequently, identifying a process owner (i.e., the person responsible for the continuous improvement of the process) is considered as a prerequisite.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Sometimes the process owner is the same person who is performing the process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Workflow is the procedural movement of information, material, and tasks from one participant to another.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Workflow includes the procedures, people and tools involved in each step of a business process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] A single workflow may either be sequential, with each step contingent upon completion of the previous one, or parallel, with multiple steps occurring simultaneously.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Multiple combinations of single workflows may be connected to achieve a resulting overall process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business process re-engineering (BPR) was originally conceptualized by Hammer and Davenport as a means to improve organizational effectiveness and productivity.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] It can involve starting from a "blank slate" and completely recreating major business processes, or it can involve comparing the "as-is" process and the "to-be" process and mapping the path for change from one to the other.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Often BPR will involve the use of information technology to secure significant performance improvement.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The term unfortunately became associated with corporate "downsizing" in the mid-1990s.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] A major part of BPM's enterprise support involves the continuous evaluation of existing processes and the identification of ways to improve upon it, resulting in a cycle of overall organizational improvement.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Knowledge management is the definition of the knowledge that employees and systems use to perform their functions and maintaining it in a format that can be accessed by others.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Duhon and the Gartner Group have defined it as "a discipline that promotes an integrated approach to identifying, capturing, evaluating, retrieving, and sharing all of an enterprise's information assets.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] These assets may include databases, documents, policies, procedures, and previously un-captured expertise and experience in individual workers." **Customer Service** Customer Service is a key component to an effective business plan.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Customer service in the 21st century is always evolving, and it is important to grow with your customer base.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Not only does a social media presence matter, but also clear communication, clear expectation setting, speed, and accuracy.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] If the customer service provided by a business is not effective, it can be detrimental to the business success.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Total quality management (TQM) emerged in the early 1980s as organizations sought to improve the quality of their products and services.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] It was followed by the Six Sigma methodology in the mid-1980s, first introduced by Motorola.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Six Sigma consists of statistical methods to improve business processes and thus reduce defects in outputs.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The "lean approach" to quality management was introduced by the Toyota Motor Company in the 1990s and focused on customer needs and reducing of wastage.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Advances in information technology over the years have changed business processes within and between business enterprises.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] In the 1960s, operating systems had limited functionality, and any workflow management systems that were in use were tailor-made for the specific organization.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The 1970s and 1980s saw the development of data-driven approaches as data storage and retrieval technologies improved.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Data modeling, rather than process modeling was the starting point for building an information system.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business processes had to adapt to information technology because process modeling was neglected.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The shift towards process-oriented management occurred in the 1990s.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Enterprise resource planning software with workflow management components such as SAP, Baan, PeopleSoft, Oracle and JD Edwards emerged, as did business process management systems (BPMS) later.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The world of e-business created a need to automate business processes across organizations, which in turn raised the need for standardized protocols and web services composition languages that can be understood across the industry.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The Business Process Modeling Notation (BPMN) and Business Motivation Model (BMM) are widely used standards for business modeling.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The most recent trends in BPM are influenced by the emergence of cloud technology, the prevalence of social media and mobile technology, and the development of analytical techniques.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Cloud-based technologies allow companies to purchase resources quickly and as required, independent of their location.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Social media, websites and smart phones are the newest channels through which organizations reach and support their customers.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business processes comprise a set of sequential sub-processes or tasks with alternative paths, depending on certain conditions as applicable, performed to achieve a given objective or produce given outputs.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Each process has one or more needed inputs.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The inputs and outputs may be received from, or sent to other business processes, other organizational units, or internal or external stakeholders.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business processes are designed to be operated by one or more business functional units, and emphasize the importance of the "process chain" rather than the individual units.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Typically, some process tasks will be manual, while some will be computer-based, and these tasks may be sequenced in many ways.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] In other words, the data and information that are being handled through the process may pass through manual or computer tasks in any given order.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The above improvement areas are equally applicable to policies, processes, detailed procedures (sub-processes/tasks) and work instructions.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] There is a cascading effect of improvements made at a higher level on those made at a lower level.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business processes must include up-to-date and accurate reports to ensure effective action.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] An example of this is the availability of purchase order status reports for supplier delivery follow-up as described in the section on effectiveness above.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] There are numerous examples of this in every possible business process.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Another example from production is the process of analyzing line rejections occurring on the shop floor.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Such a process of analysis and summarisation of line rejection events is clearly superior to a process which merely inquires into each individual rejection as it occurs.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Business process owners and operatives should realise that process improvement often occurs with introduction of appropriate transaction, operational, highlight, exception or M.I.S. reports, provided these are consciously used for day-to-day or periodical decision-making.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] With this understanding would hopefully come the willingness to invest time and other resources in business process improvement by introduction of useful and relevant reporting systems.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] The span of control is the number of subordinates a supervisor manages within a structural organization.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Introducing a business process concept has a considerable impact on the structural elements of the organization and, thus also on the span of control.
[src:erp-systems/business-process] Large organizations that are not organized as markets need to be organized in smaller units, or departments – which can be defined according to different principles.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Much business software is developed to meet the needs of a specific business, and therefore is not easily transferable to a different business environment, unless its nature and operation are identical.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Due to the unique requirements of each business, off-the-shelf software is unlikely to completely address a company's needs.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] However, where an on-the-shelf solution is necessary, due to time or monetary considerations, some level of customization is likely to be required.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Exceptions do exist, depending on the business in question, and thorough research is always required before committing to bespoke or off-the-shelf solutions.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Some business applications are interactive, i.e., they have a graphical user interface or user interface and users can query/modify/input data and view results instantaneously.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] They can also run reports instantaneously.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Some business applications run in batch mode: they are set up to run based on a predetermined event/time and a business user does not need to initiate or monitor them.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Some business applications are developed in-house, while others are purchased as off-the-shelf software products from vendors.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] These business applications are installed on either desktops or big servers.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Prior to the introduction of COBOL (a universal compiler) in 1965, businesses developed their own unique machine language.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] RCA's language consisted of 12-position instructions.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] For example, to read a record into memory, the first two digits would be the instruction (action) code.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The next four positions of the instruction (an 'A' address) would be the exact leftmost memory location where you want the readable character to be placed.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Four positions (a 'B' address) of the instruction would note the very rightmost memory location where you want the last character of the record to be located.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] A two-digit 'B' address also allows the modification of any instruction.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Instruction codes and memory designations excluded the use of 8's or 9's.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The first RCA business application was implemented in 1962 on a 4k RCA 301.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The RCA 301, mid-frame 501, and large frame 601 began their marketing in early 1960.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Technologies that previously only existed in peer-to-peer software applications, like Kazaa and Napster, are starting to appear within business applications.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Business software is designed to increase profits by cutting costs or speeding the productive cycle.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] In the early days of white-collar business automation, large mainframe computers were used to tackle the most tedious jobs, like bank cheque clearing and factory accounting.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The early use of software to replace manual white-collar labor was extremely profitable and caused a radical shift in white-collar labor.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] One computer could in many cases replace many white-collar administrative employees, without requiring any health or retirement benefits.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Building on this success, corporate consumers demanded from IBM, Hewlett-Packard, and other early suppliers, of business software to replace the old-fashioned drafting board.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Computer-aided drafting for computer-aided manufacturing (CAD-CAM) arrived in the early 1980s.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Project management software was also so valued in the early 1980s that it could cost up to $500,000 per copy.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] One of the most noticeable, widespread changes in business software was the word processor, whose rapid rise caused the decline of the ubiquitous IBM typewriter in the 1980s, as millions of companies switched to using Word Perfect, and later Microsoft Word.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Other popular computer programs for business were mathematical spreadsheet programs such as Lotus 1-2-3, and later Microsoft Excel.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] In the 1990s business shifted towards globalism, with the appearance of SAP software, which coordinates a supply-chain of vendors in order to streamline the operation of factory manufacturing.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] This process was triggered and vastly accelerated by the advent of the internet.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The next phase in the evolution of business software is being driven by the emergence of robotic process automation (RPA), which involves identifying and automating highly repetitive tasks and processes, with an aim to drive operational efficiency, reduce costs and limit human error.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Industries at the forefront of RPA adoption include the insurance industry, banking and other related financial services, the legal industry, and the healthcare industry.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Business applications are built based on the requirements of business users.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Also, these business applications are built to use certain kinds of Business transactions or data items.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] These business applications run flawlessly until there are no new business requirements or there is no change in underlying Business transactions.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Also, the business applications run flawlessly if there are no issues with computer hardware, computer networks (Internet/intranet), computer disks, power supplies, and various software components (middleware, database, computer programs, etc.).
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Business applications can fail when an unexpected error occurs.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] This error could occur due to a data error (an unexpected data input or a wrong data input), an environment error (an in infrastructure-related error), a programming error, a human error, or a workflow error.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] When a business application fails one needs to fix the business application error as soon as possible so that the business users can resume their work.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] This work of resolving business application errors is known as business application support.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The Business User calls the business application support team phone number or sends an e-mail to the business application support team.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The business application support team gets all the details of the error from the business user on the phone or from the e-mail.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] These details are then entered in a tracking software.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The tracking software creates a request number and this request number is given to the business user.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] This request number is used to track the progress on the support issue.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The request is assigned to a support team member.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] For critical business application errors (such as an application not available or an application not working correctly), an e-mail is sent to the entire organization or impacted teams so that they are aware of the issue.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] They are also provided with an estimated time for application availability.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The business application support team member collects all the necessary information about the business software error.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] This information is then recorded in the support request.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] All of the data used by the business user is also used in the investigation.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The application program is reviewed for any possible programming errors.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] If any similar business application errors occurred in the past then the issue resolution steps are retrieved from the support knowledge base and the error is resolved using those steps.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] If it is a new support error, then new issue resolution steps are created and the error is resolved.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The new support error resolution steps are recorded in the knowledge base for future use.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] For major business application errors (critical infrastructure or application failures), a phone conference call is initiated and all required support persons/teams join the call and they all work together to resolve the error.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] If the business application error occurred due to programming errors, then a request is created for the application development team to correct programming errors.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] If the business user needs new features or functions in the business application, then the required analysis/design/programming/testing/release is planned and a new version of the business software is deployed.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] If the business application error occurred due to a workflow issue or human errors during data input, then the business users are notified.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Business users then review their workflow and revise it if necessary.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] They also modify the user guide or user instructions to avoid such an error in the future.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] If the business application error occurred due to infrastructure issues, then the specific infrastructure team is notified.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The infrastructure team then implements permanent fixes for the issue and monitors the infrastructure to avoid the re-occurrence of the same error.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] The business application error tracking system is used to review all issues periodically (daily, weekly, and monthly) and reports are generated to monitor the resolved issues, repeating issues, and pending issues.
[src:erp-systems/business-software] Reports are also generated for the IT/IS management for the improvement and management of business applications.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The finance module in particular is essential to a suite of applications meeting the definition of an ERP system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The finance module provides the **system of record** for the organisation; recording the commercial impact of the business operations in the General Ledger.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP provides an integrated and continuously updated view of core business processes, typically using a shared database managed by a database management system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems track business resources—cash, raw materials, production capacity—and the status of business commitments: orders, purchase orders, and payroll.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The applications that make up the system share data across various departments (manufacturing, purchasing, sales, accounting, etc.) that provide the data.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP facilitates information flow between all business functions and manages connections to outside stakeholders.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Estimates of the size of the global ERP market range between USD $78 and $81 billion in 2026 .
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Though early ERP systems focused on large enterprises, smaller enterprises increasingly use ERP systems.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The ERP system integrates varied organizational systems and facilitates error-free transactions and production, thereby enhancing the organization's efficiency.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] However, developing an ERP system differs from traditional system development.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems run on a variety of computer hardware and network configurations, typically using a database as an information repository.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Business and technology research and advisory firm Gartner is credited for first using the acronym ERP in the 1990s.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The term captured a functional extension of two manufacturing-based concepts, material requirements planning (MRP) and manufacturing resource planning (MRP II).
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Without replacing these terms, ERP came to represent a larger whole that reflected the evolution of application integration beyond manufacturing.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Not all ERP packages are developed from a manufacturing core; ERP vendors variously began assembling their packages with finance-and-accounting, maintenance, and human-resource components.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] By the mid-1990s ERP systems addressed all core enterprise functions.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Governments and non–profit organizations also began to use ERP systems.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] An "ERP system selection methodology" is a formal process for selecting an enterprise resource planning (ERP) system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Existing methodologies include: Kuiper's funnel method, Dobrin's three-dimensional (3D) web-based decision support tool, and the Clarkston Potomac methodology.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems experienced rapid growth in the 1990s.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Because of the year 2000 problem many companies took the opportunity to replace their old systems with ERP.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems initially focused on automating back office functions that did not directly affect customers and the public.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Front office functions, such as customer relationship management (CRM), dealt directly with customers, or e-business systems such as e-commerce and e-government—or supplier relationship management (SRM) became integrated later, when the internet simplified communicating with external parties.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] "ERP II" was coined in 2000 in an article by Gartner Publications entitled *ERP Is Dead—Long Live ERP II*.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] It describes web–based software that provides real–time access to ERP systems to employees and partners (such as suppliers and customers).
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The ERP II role expands traditional ERP resource optimization and transaction processing.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Rather than just manage buying, selling, etc.—ERP II leverages information in the resources under its management to help the enterprise collaborate with other enterprises.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP II is more flexible than the first generation ERP.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Rather than confine ERP system capabilities within the organization, it goes beyond the corporate walls to interact with other systems.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Enterprise application suite is an alternate name for such systems.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP II systems are typically used to enable collaborative initiatives such as supply chain management (SCM), customer relationship management (CRM) and business intelligence (BI) among business partner organizations through the use of various electronic business technologies.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The large proportion of companies are pursuing a strong managerial targets in ERP system instead of acquire an ERP company.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Developers now make more effort to integrate mobile devices with the ERP system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP vendors are extending ERP to these devices, along with other business applications, so that businesses don't have to rely on third-party applications.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] As an example, the e-commerce platform Shopify was able to make ERP tools from Microsoft and Oracle available on its app in October 2021.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Technical stakes of modern ERP concern integration—hardware, applications, networking, supply chains.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP now covers more functions and roles—including decision making, stakeholders' relationships, standardization, transparency, globalization, etc.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] From 1999 the ERP industry underwent a paradigm shift from the existing on-premise model (i.e. separate installations of the ERP system on the client's or third-party servers) to cloud (i.e. the ERP system is served to the user via a web browser with all of it's components hosted in data centres).
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This followed the launch of early pure cloud ERP systems such as NetLedger.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This shift required massive technology and business model changes from the ERP vendors.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] An ERP system covers the following common functional areas.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Government resource planning (GRP) is the equivalent of an ERP for the public sector and an integrated office automation system for government bodies.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The software structure, modularization, core algorithms and main interfaces do not differ from other ERPs, and ERP software suppliers manage to adapt their systems to government agencies.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Most ERP systems incorporate best practices.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This means the software reflects the vendor's interpretation of the most effective way to perform each business process.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Systems vary in how conveniently the customer can modify these practices.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Use of best practices eases compliance with requirements such as International Financial Reporting Standards, Sarbanes–Oxley, or Basel II.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] They can also help comply with de facto industry standards, such as electronic funds transfer.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This is because the procedure can be readily codified within the ERP software and replicated with confidence across multiple businesses that share that business requirement.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems connect to real–time data and transaction data in a variety of ways.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] These systems are typically configured by systems integrators, who bring unique knowledge on process, equipment, and vendor solutions.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP's scope usually implies significant changes to staff work processes and practices.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Generally, three types of services are available to help implement such changes: consulting, customization, and support.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementation time depends on business size, number of modules, customization, the scope of process changes, and the readiness of the customer to take ownership for the project.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Modular ERP systems can be implemented in stages.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The typical project for a large enterprise takes about 14 months and requires around 150 consultants.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Small projects can require months; multinational and other large implementations can take years.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Customization can substantially increase implementation times.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Besides that, information processing influences various business functions e.g. some large corporations like Walmart use a just in time inventory system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This reduces inventory storage and increases delivery efficiency, and requires up-to-date data.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Before 2014, Walmart used a system called Inforem developed by IBM to manage replenishment.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The outcome of the implementation process will be significantly impacted by the skills and experience of the implementing team combined with a tried and tested implementation methodology that provides guardrails to drive the project to success.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP implementations are a specific sub-type of project however there is no industry-specified standard methodology.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementation methodologies are created by the ERP vendors or the specialist ERP consulting firms, generally known as Value Added Resellers (VARs), who carry out the implementations.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Each implementer's methodology can be assessed as to how well it meets the principles and practices outlined in the guides of the project management peak industry bodies such as Project Management Institute.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementing ERP typically requires changes in existing business processes.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Poor understanding of needed process changes prior to starting implementation is a main reason for project failure.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The difficulties could be related to the system, business process, infrastructure, training, or lack of motivation.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] It is therefore crucial that organizations thoroughly analyze processes before they deploy an ERP software.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Analysis can identify opportunities for process modernization.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] It also enables an assessment of the alignment of current processes with those provided by the ERP system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP implementation is considerably more difficult (and politically charged) in decentralized organizations, because they often have different processes, business rules, data semantics, authorization hierarchies, and decision centers.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This may require migrating some business units before others, delaying implementation to work through the necessary changes for each unit, possibly reducing integration (e.g., linking via master data management) or customizing the system to meet specific needs.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] A potential disadvantage is that adopting "standard" processes can lead to a loss of competitive advantage.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] While this has happened, losses in one area are often offset by gains in other areas, increasing overall competitive advantage.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Configuring an ERP system is largely a matter of balancing the way the organization wants the system to work, and the way the system is designed to work out of the box.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems typically include many configurable settings that in effect modify system operations.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, in the ServiceNow platform, business rules can be written requiring the signature of a business owner within 2 weeks of a newly completed risk assessment.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The tool can be configured to automatically email notifications to the business owner, and transition the risk assessment to various stages in the process depending on the owner's responses or lack thereof.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Two-tier ERP software and hardware lets companies run the equivalent of two ERP systems at once: one at the corporate level and one at the division or subsidiary level.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, a manufacturing company could use an ERP system to manage across the organization using independent global or regional distribution, production or sales centers, and service providers to support the main company's customers.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Each independent center (or) subsidiary may have its own business operations cycles, workflows, and business processes.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Given the realities of globalization, enterprises continuously evaluate how to optimize their regional, divisional, and product or manufacturing strategies to support strategic goals and reduce time-to-market while increasing profitability and delivering value.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] With two-tier ERP, the regional distribution, production, or sales centers and service providers continue operating under their own business model—separate from the main company, using their own ERP systems.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Since these smaller companies' processes and workflows are not tied to main company's processes and workflows, they can respond to local business requirements in multiple locations.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] An alternative to a two-tier approach is to use as an ERP system which allows for multiple workflows to be configured for the same function.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This allows each operation or division to have its own workflow, say for order entry.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This avoids the need to integrate two ERP systems as all divisions and operations are running within the same ERP system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems are theoretically based on industry best practices, and their makers intend that organizations deploy them "as is".
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP vendors do offer customers configuration options that let organizations incorporate their own business rules, but gaps in features often remain even after configuration is complete.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP customers have several options to reconcile feature gaps, each with their own pros/cons.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Technical solutions include rewriting part of the delivered software, writing a homegrown module to work within the ERP system, or interfacing to an external system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] These three options constitute varying degrees of system customization—with the first being the most invasive and costly to maintain.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Alternatively, there are non-technical options such as changing business practices or organizational policies to better match the delivered ERP feature set.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems can be extended with third-party software, often via vendor-supplied interfaces.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Data migration is the process of moving, copying, and restructuring data from an existing system to an enterprise resource planning (ERP) system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] It is a critical component of a successful implementation and requires thorough planning.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] However, because migration typically occurs near the end of the implementation process, it often receives inadequate attention.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Often, data migration is incomplete because some of the data in the existing system is either incompatible or not needed in the new system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] As such, the existing system may need to be kept as an archived database to refer back to once the new ERP system is in place.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The most fundamental advantage of ERP is that the integration of a myriad of business processes saves time and expense.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Management can make decisions faster and with fewer errors.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Data becomes visible across the organization.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Research published in 2011 based on a survey of 225 manufacturers, retailers and distributors found "high" rates of interest and adoption of ERP systems and that very few businesses were "completely untouched" by the concept of an ERP system.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] 27% of the companies survey had a fully operational system, 12% were at that time rolling out a system and 26% had an existing ERP system which they were extending or upgrading.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The term "postmodern ERP" was coined by Gartner in 2013, when it first appeared in the paper series "Predicts 2014".
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The basic idea is that there should still be a core ERP solution that would cover most important business functions, while other functions will be covered by specialist software solutions that merely extend the core ERP.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] This concept is similar to the "best-of-breed" approach to software execution, but it shouldn't be confused with it.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] While in both cases, applications that make up the whole are relatively loosely connected and quite easily interchangeable, in the case of the latter there is no ERP solution whatsoever.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] Instead, every business function is covered by a separate software solution.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] There is, however, no golden rule as to what business functions should be part of the core ERP, and what should be covered by supplementary solutions.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] According to Gartner, every company must define their own postmodern ERP strategy, based on company's internal and external needs, operations and processes.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, a company may define that the core ERP solution should cover those business processes that must stay behind the firewall, and therefore, choose to leave their core ERP on-premises.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] At the same time, another company may adopt a hybrid ERP approach, hosting the core ERP solution in the cloud while moving only a few ERP modules as supplementary solutions to on-premises.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The main benefits that companies will gain from implementing postmodern ERP strategy are speed and flexibility when reacting to unexpected changes in business processes or on the organizational level.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] With the majority of applications having a relatively loose connection, it is fairly easy to replace or upgrade them whenever necessary.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] In addition to that, following the examples above, companies can select and combine cloud-based and on-premises solutions that are most suited for their ERP needs.
[src:erp-systems/enterprise-resource-planning] The downside of postmodern ERP is that it will most likely lead to an increased number of software vendors that companies will have to manage, as well as pose additional integration challenges for the central IT.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] This is not exclusively a software function, but the management of people skills, requiring a dedication to database accuracy, and sufficient computer resources.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] It is a total company management concept for using human and company resources more productively.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRP II is not a single specific proprietary software system and can thus take many forms.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] It is almost impossible to visualize an MRP II system that does not use a computer.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] An MRP II system can be based on either purchased–licensed or in-house software.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Almost every MRP II system is modular in construction.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] The MRP II system integrates these modules together so that they use common data and freely exchange information, in a model of how a manufacturing enterprise should and can operate.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] The MRP II approach is therefore very different from the "point solution" approach, where individual systems are deployed to help a company plan, control or manage a specific activity.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRP II is by definition fully integrated or at least fully interfaced.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Material requirements planning (MRP) and manufacturing resource planning (MRPII) are predecessors of enterprise resource planning (ERP), a business information integration system.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] The development of these manufacturing coordination and integration methods and tools made today's ERP systems possible.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Both MRP and MRPII are still widely used, independently and as modules of more comprehensive ERP systems, but the original vision of integrated information systems as we know them today began with the development of MRP and MRPII in manufacturing.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRP (and MRPII) evolved from the earliest commercial database management package developed by Gene Thomas at IBM in the 1960s.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] The original structure was called BOMP (bill-of-materials processor), which evolved in the next generation into a more generalized tool called DBOMP (Database Organization and Maintenance Program).
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] These were run on mainframes, such as IBM/360.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] The vision for MRP and MRPII was to centralize and integrate business information in a way that would facilitate decision making for production line managers and increase the efficiency of the production line overall.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] In the 1980s, manufacturers developed systems for calculating the resource requirements of a production run based on sales forecasts.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] In order to calculate the raw materials needed to produce products and to schedule the purchase of those materials along with the machine and labor time needed, production managers recognized that they would need to use computer and software technology to manage the information.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Originally, manufacturing operations built custom software programs that ran on mainframes.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Material requirements planning (MRP) was an early iteration of the integrated information systems vision.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRP information systems helped managers determine the quantity and timing of raw materials purchases.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Information systems that would assist managers with other parts of the manufacturing process, MRPII, followed.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] While MRP was primarily concerned with materials, MRPII was concerned with the integration of all aspects of the manufacturing process, including materials, finance and human resources.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Like today's ERP systems, MRPII was designed to tell us about a lot of information by way of a centralized database.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] However, the hardware, software, and relational database technology of the 1980s was not advanced enough to provide the speed and capacity to run these systems in real-time, and the cost of these systems was prohibitive for most businesses.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Nonetheless, the vision had been established, and shifts in the underlying business processes along with rapid advances in technology led to the more affordable enterprise and application integration systems that big businesses and many medium and smaller businesses use today.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRP is concerned primarily with manufacturing materials while MRPII is concerned with the coordination of the entire manufacturing production, including materials, finance, and human resources.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] The goal of MRPII is to provide consistent data to all members in the manufacturing process as the product moves through the production line.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] In addition, some data is unreliable in non-integrated systems because the same data is categorized differently in the individual databases used by different functional areas.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRPII systems begin with MRP, material requirements planning.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRP allows for the input of sales forecasts from sales and marketing, or of actual sales demand in the form of customers orders.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] These demands determine the raw materials demand.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] MRP and MRPII systems draw on a master production schedule, the breakdown of specific plans for each product on a line.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] While MRP allows for the coordination of raw materials purchasing, MRPII facilitates the development of a detailed production schedule that accounts for machine and labor capacity, scheduling the production runs according to the arrival of materials.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] An MRPII output is a final labor and machine schedule.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Data about the cost of production, including machine time, labor time and materials used, as well as final production numbers, is provided from the MRPII system to accounting and finance.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] For the companies that want to integrate their other departments with their manufacturing management, ERP software are necessary.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Authors like Pochet and Wolsey argue that MRP and MRP II, as well as the planning modules in current APS and ERP systems, are actually sets of heuristics.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] Better production plans could be obtained by optimization over more powerful mathematical programming models, usually integer programming models.
[src:erp-systems/manufacturing-resource-planning] While they acknowledge that the use of heuristics, like those prescribed by MRP and MRP II, were necessary in the past due to lack of computational power to solve complex optimization models, this is mitigated to some extent by recent improvements in computers.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] Prior to MRP, and before computers dominated industry, reorder point (ROP)/reorder-quantity (ROQ) type methods like EOQ (economic order quantity) had been used in manufacturing and inventory management.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] MRP was computerized by the aero engine makers Rolls-Royce and General Electric in the early 1950s but not commercialized by them.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] It was then 'reinvented' to supply the Polaris program and then, in 1964, as a response to the Toyota Manufacturing Program, Joseph Orlicky developed material requirements planning (MRP).
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] Early MRP users in the 1960s and 1970s included Black & Decker, Twin Disc, Markem, Steelcase, and American Sterilizer.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] The first company was Black and Decker in 1964, with Dick Alban as project leader.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] Orlicky's 1975 book *Material Requirements Planning* has the subtitle *The New Way of Life in Production and Inventory Management*.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] By 1975, MRP was implemented in 700 companies.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] This number had grown to about 8,000 by 1981.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] In 1983, Oliver Wight developed MRP into manufacturing resource planning (MRP II).
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] In the 1980s, Joe Orlicky's MRP evolved into Oliver Wight's manufacturing resource planning (MRP II) which brings master scheduling, rough-cut capacity planning, capacity requirements planning, S&OP in 1983 and other concepts to classical MRP.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] By 1989, about one third of the software industry was MRP II software sold to American industry ($1.2 billion worth of software).
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] MRP's appeal is greater financial improvement than other business software.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] While automating payroll reduces the need for payroll clerks but requires computer equipment and staff, *Computerworld* said in 1986 that "In companies getting the full benefits of MRP II, however, the return on investment averages 200%".
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] While accounting software automates manual functions, MRP allows analyses of updated material requirements impossible without computers.
[src:erp-systems/material-requirements-planning] By then a variety of MRP software was available for mainframes and minicomputers, such as ASK's Manman and IBM's MAPICS.
